WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:14.000
FEDERATED IDENTITY MANAGEMENT

00:14.000 --> 00:16.000
FEDERATED IDENTITY MANAGEMENT

00:16.000 --> 00:20.000
Let's talk about what this looks like from user's perspective.

00:20.000 --> 00:34.000
FEDERATED IDENTITY MANAGEMENT

00:34.000 --> 00:36.000
FEDERATED IDENTITY MANAGEMENT

00:36.000 --> 00:40.000
Let's talk about what this looks like from user's perspective.

00:40.000 --> 00:44.000
From user's perspective, they can log in once, usually with their corporate credentials,

00:44.000 --> 00:48.000
and then magically get access to a bunch of different systems.

00:48.000 --> 00:51.000
Sounds just like single sign on, doesn't it?

00:51.000 --> 00:57.000
But there's a really important difference between FEDERATED IDENTITY MANAGEMENT and single sign on.

00:57.000 --> 01:02.000
And the key difference is that single sign on is typically only within one organization,

01:02.000 --> 01:06.000
and it only enables access to one organization's systems,

01:06.000 --> 01:14.000
whereas FEDERATED IDENTITY MANAGEMENT is allowing users to access multiple different entities systems.

01:14.000 --> 01:18.000
So let's start with an example to kind of put this into the real world.

01:18.000 --> 01:22.000
So let's think of how when you're browsing the web nowadays,

01:22.000 --> 01:28.000
there's lots of websites that you can go to where instead of having a unique username and password on that website,

01:28.000 --> 01:34.000
instead what you have is it gives you the website, will give you the ability to log in with Google or Facebook,

01:34.000 --> 01:37.000
or your Amazon ID, or something like that.

01:37.000 --> 01:40.000
So let's pick Facebook as an example.

01:40.000 --> 01:45.000
And let's try and think of a company that Facebook doesn't yet own.

01:45.000 --> 01:48.000
It's genuinely difficult to think of a company that they don't own yet.

01:48.000 --> 01:50.000
Spotify. I don't think they own Spotify yet.

01:50.000 --> 01:52.000
So let's go with them, for example, okay?

01:52.000 --> 01:55.000
So here's how this would work.

01:55.000 --> 01:58.000
If I go to Spotify.com, and I go to Login,

01:58.000 --> 02:02.000
instead of providing a unique username and password for Spotify.com,

02:02.000 --> 02:06.000
instead I click the button that says Login with Facebook.

02:06.000 --> 02:08.000
And then what will happen is a window will come up.

02:08.000 --> 02:12.000
And what do I type in there? I type in my Facebook credentials.

02:12.000 --> 02:18.000
And I essentially log in and I'm identified and authenticated by Facebook.

02:18.000 --> 02:21.000
And then when that Facebook has authenticated me,

02:21.000 --> 02:24.000
I'm then able to log in to Spotify.

02:24.000 --> 02:27.000
This is exactly what Federated Access Management is.

02:27.000 --> 02:32.000
It's a trust relationship between three entities.

02:32.000 --> 02:34.000
You've got your user or your principal.

02:34.000 --> 02:37.000
That's the person who's actually logging in.

02:37.000 --> 02:40.000
You've got your identity provider.

02:40.000 --> 02:43.000
This is the entity that stores the user's identity,

02:43.000 --> 02:47.000
their account, and knows the user's username and password,

02:47.000 --> 02:51.000
or whatever they authenticate with knowledge, ownership, or characteristic.

02:51.000 --> 02:54.000
And then the third entity in the trust relationship

02:54.000 --> 02:58.000
is the relying party or the service provider

02:58.000 --> 03:00.000
that the user actually wants to access.

03:00.000 --> 03:02.000
So in the example that we just talked about,

03:02.000 --> 03:04.000
let's relate who each of the entities are.

03:04.000 --> 03:08.000
So the user principal, that's obviously the person that's logging in.

03:08.000 --> 03:14.000
The website that the person ultimately wanted to access was Spotify.

03:14.000 --> 03:19.000
So Spotify would be the relying party or another term for this is service provider.

03:19.000 --> 03:22.000
So relying party service provider means the same thing.

03:22.000 --> 03:25.000
That's the entity the user actually wants to access.

03:25.000 --> 03:28.000
But the user didn't authenticate with the relying party.

03:28.000 --> 03:31.000
Instead the user authenticated with Facebook.

03:31.000 --> 03:33.000
So in the example here that I've just given you,

03:33.000 --> 03:35.000
Facebook would be the identity provider.

03:35.000 --> 03:39.000
The way this works in most corporations is that the user will authenticate

03:39.000 --> 03:42.000
with the corporate credentials, usually through Active Directory.

03:42.000 --> 03:46.000
And then, because most organizations nowadays have all sorts of cloud services,

03:46.000 --> 03:51.000
what the user is able to magically access through their corporate credentials

03:51.000 --> 03:55.000
is things like service now and concur and all these online software

03:55.000 --> 03:56.000
is a service application.

03:56.000 --> 03:59.000
So that's the idea behind federated access.

03:59.000 --> 04:03.000
It's a trust relationship between at least three entities.

04:03.000 --> 04:11.000
The user, the identity provider, and one or more relying parties or service providers.

04:11.000 --> 04:17.000
Now there's a number of different protocols or standards that will enable federated access.

04:17.000 --> 04:20.000
The major one that you need to know about is SAML,

04:20.000 --> 04:23.000
the security assertion markup language.

04:23.000 --> 04:26.000
And SAML actually has two capabilities.

04:26.000 --> 04:30.000
It does both authentication and authorization.

04:30.000 --> 04:33.000
And we'll talk about SAML in a bit more detail in a moment.

04:33.000 --> 04:35.000
And it's very commonly on the exam.

04:35.000 --> 04:38.000
So it's one of the protocols you need to know a bit about.

04:38.000 --> 04:43.000
Three other protocols that enable federated access that I would suggest you just know at a high level.

04:43.000 --> 04:45.000
You don't need to know any great detail on them.

04:45.000 --> 04:50.000
RWS Federation, which does both authentication and authorization.

04:50.000 --> 04:54.000
And two more open ID and OAuth.

04:54.000 --> 05:00.000
Open ID by itself only does the identification and the authentication.

05:00.000 --> 05:03.000
OAuth on the other hand does the authorization.

05:03.000 --> 05:10.000
And so these two protocols are typically work together to achieve both the authentication and the authorization.

05:10.000 --> 05:13.000
Now let's dig into SAML in a little more detail.

05:13.000 --> 05:21.000
And just like we talked about with Kerberos, SAML uses this idea of having tickets or tokens that are passed back and forth.

05:21.000 --> 05:26.000
So let's say the user wants to log into the, here we've called it the service provider.

05:26.000 --> 05:28.000
Otherwise known as the relying party.

05:28.000 --> 05:31.000
Let's say the user wants to log into the service provider.

05:31.000 --> 05:35.000
The first thing the user will do is send a request saying, I'd like to log in.

05:35.000 --> 05:45.000
Now if the user does not currently have a valid ticket or token, what's going to happen is the user is going to be redirected back to the identity provider.

05:45.000 --> 05:48.000
So that the user can authenticate themselves.

05:48.000 --> 05:53.000
So the user will be redirected back to the identity provider, maybe something like Active Directory.

05:53.000 --> 06:00.000
The user will then authenticate themselves through knowledge, ownership, or characteristic, or some combination thereof.

06:00.000 --> 06:08.000
And once the user is authenticated, the user will be given a SAML assertion, ticket, or token.

06:08.000 --> 06:12.000
And it's really important to understand what this contains, what this ticket or token contains.

06:12.000 --> 06:17.000
It contains some assertion statements, some information on the user.

06:17.000 --> 06:21.000
Maybe what their username is, what their role is, what sort of access they should have.

06:21.000 --> 06:27.000
But very importantly, and listen carefully here, it does not contain their authentication information.

06:27.000 --> 06:32.000
And by that I mean it would not contain their password or their biometric data or anything like that.

06:32.000 --> 06:39.000
That data is not contained in the ticket or token because the relying party has no idea what the user's password is.

06:39.000 --> 06:46.000
And you don't want them to because the whole point of federated access is that we're letting our users log into different service providers.

06:46.000 --> 06:51.000
And you would not want those service providers to know your users corporate credentials.

06:51.000 --> 07:00.000
So once the user authenticates, gets their ticket or token, they can then take that ticket or token and pass it back to the relying party or the service provider.

07:00.000 --> 07:06.000
So we'll then read through the assertion statements inside that ticket or token and make an authorization decision.

07:06.000 --> 07:11.000
What is the user going to be authorized to access in this particular service provider?

07:11.000 --> 07:15.000
And then if the user is allowed in, they'll get access.

07:15.000 --> 07:18.000
So that's the basic steps that SAML goes through.

07:18.000 --> 07:21.000
And there's a couple major things that you should know about SAML.

07:21.000 --> 07:29.000
As I mentioned, it uses this concept of tickets or tokens and these tickets or tokens contain assertion statements.

07:29.000 --> 07:33.000
And those assertion statements are written in a particular language or protocol.

07:33.000 --> 07:37.000
It's known as XML, the extensible markup language.

07:37.000 --> 07:45.000
This is simply a language that is both human and machine readable and it's what those assertion statements are written in within the SAML ticket or token.

07:45.000 --> 07:56.000
The final piece that you should know about SAML is some of the major components that are always required to actually send SAML authentication and authorization information between these different entities.

07:57.000 --> 08:01.000
And the four major components of SAML are first the assertion.

08:01.000 --> 08:04.000
And the assertion is what we just talked about.

08:04.000 --> 08:12.000
That's those assertion statements contained within the ticket or token, containing the authentication and authorization information and some other attributes.

08:12.000 --> 08:16.000
The next component is what we call the protocol.

08:16.000 --> 08:25.000
And this is simply defines how the different entities in that trust relationship actually communicate with each other, defines how they talk to each other.

08:26.000 --> 08:29.000
The next piece is what is known as the bindings.

08:29.000 --> 08:34.000
The bindings define how the SAML assertion information is actually sent across the network.

08:34.000 --> 08:37.000
So for instance, you can bind it to HTTP.

08:37.000 --> 08:41.000
So the SAML assertion information is sent over the HTTP protocol.

08:41.000 --> 08:44.000
And the final piece is what are known as profiles.

08:44.000 --> 08:47.000
You can set up SAML to have different profiles.

08:47.000 --> 08:50.000
In other words, to serve different business purposes.

08:50.000 --> 08:54.000
So one usage of SAML might be for web application authentication.

08:54.000 --> 08:57.000
Another use might be for connecting to say the LDAP system.

08:57.000 --> 09:03.000
So you can set up different profiles to allow for different business uses of SAML.

09:03.000 --> 09:05.000
So there you go. That's federated access.

